<div id="review_2702729383" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2702729383" />
    <a title="Amanda " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4929450-amanda"><img alt="Amanda " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627259389p2/4929450.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2702729383?book_show_action=true">Apr 05, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda " href="/user/show/4929450-amanda">Amanda </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2702729383" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14502003234424266978">I thought that there were a lot of important messages and things to ponder in this book. Manning starts off the book by talking about faith. <br/><br/>He says <i>&quot;Most Americans would define faith as the belief in the existence of God. In earlier times, faith had to do more with one’s relationship with God and rather, if one trusted in God.&quot;</i> The first is a matter of the head, the second is a matter of the heart. The first can leave us unchanged, the second leaves us intrinsically changed.<br/><br/>He talked about a lo</span>
  <span id="freeText14502003234424266978" style="display:none">I thought that there were a lot of important messages and things to ponder in this book. Manning starts off the book by talking about faith. <br /><br />He says <i>"Most Americans would define faith as the belief in the existence of God. In earlier times, faith had to do more with one’s relationship with God and rather, if one trusted in God."</i> The first is a matter of the head, the second is a matter of the heart. The first can leave us unchanged, the second leaves us intrinsically changed.<br /><br />He talked about a lot of things that made me pause and assess my own beliefs and how they aligned (or didn't) to the Good News. <br /><br /><i>"Hypocrisy is the natural expression of what is meanest in us all."</i><br /><br /><i>"Indecision means that we stop growing for an indeterminate length of time. We get stuck. A sad Christian is a phony Christian and a guilty Christian is no Christian at all."</i><br /><br /><i>"The Christian with depth is the person who’s failed and learned to live with it. Procrastination is perhaps the worst, most damaging sin of all."</i><br /><br />On the downside, I did notice some Scripture being twisted to suit his narrative. Manning recalled that in Mark 10:13-16, the story where the disciples were trying to turn away the children whose parents wanted them to see Jesus, that he "silenced the [disciples] with a withering glance," even though the actual Scripture passage never mentioned the "withering glance."<br /><br />I'm not sure if he was imposing his own views of Jesus' words for us to "become like little children" or whether his beliefs can be directly extracted from Scripture and I think this would be confusing and/or misleading for someone who doesn't have an extensive background in biblical knowledge.<br /><br />For being a book on the Christian faith, there was very little reference to Scripture in this book. The book mostly centered around anecdotes from the author's own life as well as those collated from outside sources. This book seems to be Christian light, the Young Life of outreach books, not so much intended for longtime believers but for ones who are dabbling in the faith but are unsure whether or not to make the jump. If this is Manning's intention, I'm not sure how successful this book will be in being the impetus to cause a reader to make a declarative decision about their faith.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14502003234424266978" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

